A: The problem is that you are writing strings without a line break. But BufferedReader expects one of the line characters mentioned above which you are not providing. It does output the whole buffer once the end of the stream is reached though.
You should use printWriter.println() instead of printWriter.write(). println() automatically appends a line separator at the end of the string.
Try this:
printWriter.println("1");
printWriter.println("2");
printWriter.println("3");


A: You are using PrintWriter.write() which writes the string as is. You should use PrintWriter.println() which writes the string and then terminates the line.
So, you should replace:
printWriter.write("1");
printWriter.write("2");
printWriter.write("3");

with:
printWriter.println("1");
printWriter.println("2");
printWriter.println("3");


A: You are writing the strings without a line break. BufferedReader reads until it encounters a line separator, which you are not providing. You can use printWriter.println() to write the strings and include a line break.
Try this:
printWriter.println("1");
printWriter.println("2");
printWriter.println("3");


